WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.540 --> 00:00:10.330
MALE SPEAKER: Good morning,
and welcome to Talks at google

00:00:10.330 --> 00:00:13.060
in Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:00:13.060 --> 00:00:18.260
Today, it's my great pleasure to
introduce Dr. Angelo Volandes.

00:00:18.260 --> 00:00:22.850
He joins us today to discuss his
new book, "The Conversation-- A

00:00:22.850 --> 00:00:27.640
Revolutionary Plan
For End-of-Life Care."

00:00:27.640 --> 00:00:30.170
Dr. Volandes believes
that a life well

00:00:30.170 --> 00:00:33.210
lived deserves a good ending.

00:00:33.210 --> 00:00:36.550
Through the stories of seven
patients with very different

00:00:36.550 --> 00:00:39.870
end-of-life experiences,
he demonstrates

00:00:39.870 --> 00:00:41.830
that what seriously
ill people who

00:00:41.830 --> 00:00:43.670
are approaching the
end of their lives

00:00:43.670 --> 00:00:46.560
need most is not
new technologies,

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:50.270
but one simple thing,
"the conversation."

00:00:50.270 --> 00:00:52.880
He argues for a
radical re-envisioning

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:55.420
of the patient-doctor
relationship,

00:00:55.420 --> 00:00:58.660
and offers ways for
patients and their families

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:01.360
to talk about this
difficult issue

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:03.960
to ensure that patients
will be in charge

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:06.300
of their medical care.

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:09.270
Dr. Volandes is a
physician and researcher

00:01:09.270 --> 00:01:12.820
at Harvard Medical School
and Mass General Hospital.

00:01:12.820 --> 00:01:16.400
He's the Co-founder of Advanced
Care Planning Decisions,

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:20.950
a nonprofit organization devoted
to encouraging the conversation

00:01:20.950 --> 00:01:22.810
through the use of videos.

00:01:22.810 --> 00:01:26.875
Please join me in
welcoming Dr. Volandes.

00:01:26.875 --> 00:01:28.250
ANGELO VOLANDES:
So good morning.

00:01:28.250 --> 00:01:29.250
Thanks a lot for coming.

00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:30.590
I really appreciate it.

00:01:30.590 --> 00:01:33.700
It's a real privilege to present
some of the work that I do,

00:01:33.700 --> 00:01:36.720
and especially here at
Google, because you all

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:39.980
tackle some of the most
difficult problems facing

00:01:39.980 --> 00:01:41.200
our society.

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:42.880
And what I'm going
to talk about today

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:47.280
is what I feel is the most
urgent problem in health care

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:47.780
today.

00:01:47.780 --> 00:01:50.740
So maybe you can help
me think about it.

00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:54.560
When we asked most people
where do they want to die,

00:01:54.560 --> 00:01:55.925
where do they tell us?

00:01:55.925 --> 00:01:56.550
AUDIENCE: Home.

00:01:56.550 --> 00:01:57.950
ANGELO VOLANDES: Home.

00:01:57.950 --> 00:02:00.040
Most Americans want
to die at home.

00:02:00.040 --> 00:02:03.560
In fact, in the latest
survey, 86% of Americans

00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:06.910
want to die at home,
surrounded by their loved ones,

00:02:06.910 --> 00:02:08.919
and in comfort.

00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:10.310
But what are the facts?

00:02:10.310 --> 00:02:12.806
Where do most people die
in our country today?

00:02:12.806 --> 00:02:13.760
AUDIENCE: Hospitals.

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:15.210
ANGELO VOLANDES: Hospitals.

00:02:15.210 --> 00:02:18.440
People over the age
of 65, 2/3 of them

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:21.280
will die in a
hospital or nursing

00:02:21.280 --> 00:02:24.820
home, often tethered to a
machine and in a good deal

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:27.080
of pain and suffering.

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:31.200
This misalignment between the
type of medical care people

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:34.150
want and the type of
medical care they end up

00:02:34.150 --> 00:02:36.350
getting in our health
care system today

00:02:36.350 --> 00:02:41.860
is what I feel is the most
urgent problem in health care.

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:43.760
Now, you've all been
reading about it.

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:45.760
On the front page of
"The New York Times"

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:47.940
there's been a story
about the problem.

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:51.810
And we usually talk about
it in terms of cost.

00:02:51.810 --> 00:02:55.800
Yes, end-of-life care
is, indeed, costly.

00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:58.270
But by the end of
our time together, I

00:02:58.270 --> 00:03:02.410
hope to throw in two other
phrases, two other lenses

00:03:02.410 --> 00:03:04.960
from which to
understand this problem.

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:09.230
When Americans get
care in hospitals

00:03:09.230 --> 00:03:12.500
that if they were more
informed they would not want,

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:17.120
let's call it for what it
is-- it's unwanted care.

00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:20.150
And when people get unwanted
care in our health care system

00:03:20.150 --> 00:03:23.950
today, it's truly
a medical error.

00:03:23.950 --> 00:03:26.760
It's no different than
a surgeon operating

00:03:26.760 --> 00:03:32.710
on the wrong side of the body,
or an ICU doctor not following

00:03:32.710 --> 00:03:36.180
a checklist for a patient
on a breathing machine.

00:03:36.180 --> 00:03:38.180
But we don't want to
just talk about problems.

00:03:38.180 --> 00:03:40.860
What are some
potential solutions?

00:03:40.860 --> 00:03:43.800
For me, I feel that
the primary reason

00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:47.480
why people get unwanted care
in our health care system today

00:03:47.480 --> 00:03:51.930
is because doctors are not
slowing down, sitting down,

00:03:51.930 --> 00:03:57.110
and having the conversation--
an honest and frank discussion

00:03:57.110 --> 00:04:02.080
with patients and family members
about what's important to them.

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:05.900
But, you know, today we live
in a visually-literate society.

00:04:05.900 --> 00:04:09.790
We're a YouTube generation,
and that's true of all ages.

00:04:09.790 --> 00:04:12.540
And sometimes words
are not enough.

00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:16.579
Sometimes we need images to
help people better understand

00:04:16.579 --> 00:04:17.709
their options.

00:04:17.709 --> 00:04:19.300
So I'm also going
to talk about how

00:04:19.300 --> 00:04:24.110
to enhance those
conversations with videos.

00:04:24.110 --> 00:04:26.390
But before I get
started, I thought

00:04:26.390 --> 00:04:31.280
I'd begin with a story-- this
is, after all, a book reading.

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:33.460
Meet Professor Helen Thompson.

00:04:33.460 --> 00:04:37.940
Helen Thompson was one of
the foremost literary critics

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:40.440
on the poetry of Walt Whitman.

00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:42.640
How many of you are
familiar with the poetry

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:44.240
of Walt Whitman?

00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:45.320
Great.

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:49.640
So there's definitely a
generational gap there.

00:04:49.640 --> 00:04:52.690
I was born and bred in
Brooklyn, New York-- you'll

00:04:52.690 --> 00:04:55.740
hear my accent occasionally--
where Walt Whitman spent

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:57.480
the first half of his life.

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:01.340
So every other street corner
had a Whitman Elementary School,

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:04.270
and all the pupils
were forced to memorize

00:05:04.270 --> 00:05:07.110
the opening lines of
Whitman's magnum opus,

00:05:07.110 --> 00:05:09.040
"The Leaves of Grass."

00:05:09.040 --> 00:05:10.860
So Professor Thompson
and I hit it off

00:05:10.860 --> 00:05:13.440
because we could both
recite those lines.

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:17.390
"I celebrate myself
and sing myself.

00:05:17.390 --> 00:05:20.070
And what I assume
you shall assume,

00:05:20.070 --> 00:05:25.710
for every atom belonging to
me as good, belongs to you."

00:05:25.710 --> 00:05:27.570
Now, you may be
asking yourself why

00:05:27.570 --> 00:05:31.430
I'm telling you about Helen
Thompson or the poetry of Walt

00:05:31.430 --> 00:05:32.480
Whitman.

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:34.720
Well, what I haven't told
you is that Helen Thompson

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:37.180
was my patient a few years ago.

00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:39.760
What I haven't told you
is that Helen Thompson

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:43.120
was a 56-year-old female with
brain cancer being admitted

00:05:43.120 --> 00:05:45.220
to my hospital service.

00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:50.110
What I haven't told you is
that Helen Thompson was dying.

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:53.110
And so I conducted a history.

00:05:53.110 --> 00:05:55.150
I did my physical exam.

00:05:55.150 --> 00:05:57.860
And then I got to
that point where

00:05:57.860 --> 00:06:01.400
doctors get a little
bit uncomfortable with,

00:06:01.400 --> 00:06:07.170
where the words of Whitman
metamorphosed into other words.

00:06:07.170 --> 00:06:14.550
Words like CPR, ventilators,
the ICU, goals of care, hospice.

00:06:14.550 --> 00:06:16.790
In other words,
the vocabulary of

00:06:16.790 --> 00:06:20.410
shared decision-making
at the end of life.

00:06:20.410 --> 00:06:23.040
And I looked at the professor
and I said, "Professor,

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:26.360
you've seen scores
of doctors since you

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:29.460
were diagnosed, and by the
time that you're seeing me.

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:32.610
Have you ever had the
conversation with them?"

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:34.800
And she gave me
that blank stare.

00:06:34.800 --> 00:06:37.430
And so I proceeded to
ask her those questions.

00:06:37.430 --> 00:06:39.210
What's important to you?

00:06:39.210 --> 00:06:41.370
What's a good day for you?

00:06:41.370 --> 00:06:44.740
Where did you want to spend
whatever remaining time you

00:06:44.740 --> 00:06:45.960
have?

00:06:45.960 --> 00:06:50.221
Where are you on this
journey with your illness?

00:06:50.221 --> 00:06:52.470
And then she looked at me
and give me that blank stare

00:06:52.470 --> 00:06:55.250
that I think a lot of
patients give doctors when

00:06:55.250 --> 00:06:57.270
they have this conversation.

00:06:57.270 --> 00:07:00.390
And so I naively asked
her, I said, "Professor,

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:03.420
would you take a walk with
me to the Intensive Care Unit

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:06.840
so I can actually show
you some of these things?"

00:07:06.840 --> 00:07:08.230
Of course she obliged.

00:07:08.230 --> 00:07:09.910
We didn't walk to the ICU.

00:07:09.910 --> 00:07:12.760
I put her in a wheelchair
and rolled her down

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:14.950
to the Intensive Care Unit.

00:07:14.950 --> 00:07:17.340
I got to show her a ventilator.

00:07:17.340 --> 00:07:21.096
I got to show her a patient
on a breathing machine.

00:07:21.096 --> 00:07:22.720
There were a couple
of residents there.

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:25.430
One was performing
a lumbar puncture,

00:07:25.430 --> 00:07:28.070
another one was
inserting a central line.

00:07:28.070 --> 00:07:30.280
And what the professor
was able to do

00:07:30.280 --> 00:07:33.250
was to get a sense of the
place-- hear the beeps

00:07:33.250 --> 00:07:35.860
and buzzes, see the
colorful monitors,

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:39.860
to feel the rhythm of
the Intensive Care Unit.

00:07:39.860 --> 00:07:43.240
Now, as fate would have it-- I
obviously did not plan on this,

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:46.970
but there was a code blue in
the ICU while we were there,

00:07:46.970 --> 00:07:50.670
and I immediately brought her
out of the Intensive Care Unit,

00:07:50.670 --> 00:07:55.430
but not before she caught
a few glimpses of CPR.

00:07:55.430 --> 00:07:58.370
When we went back to her
room, she looked at me

00:07:58.370 --> 00:08:02.260
and said, "Words, words, words.

00:08:02.260 --> 00:08:05.030
Angelo, I understood
every single word

00:08:05.030 --> 00:08:06.090
that you said before.

00:08:06.090 --> 00:08:09.000
CPR, breathing
machines, comfort care.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:12.680
I am, after all, a
professor of English.

00:08:12.680 --> 00:08:17.150
But I had no idea that's
what you were talking about.

00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:20.210
It doesn't look like
that on television."

00:08:20.210 --> 00:08:21.740
And that's when
it occurred to me,

00:08:21.740 --> 00:08:25.580
so often health care, we're
having these conversations

00:08:25.580 --> 00:08:28.110
with our patients
and family members,

00:08:28.110 --> 00:08:31.070
but they're thinking about
what's on the television

00:08:31.070 --> 00:08:34.480
and that CPR works all the
time, and that everybody

00:08:34.480 --> 00:08:37.370
looks like George Clooney
on a breathing machine.

00:08:37.370 --> 00:08:40.179
The clinical reality
is very different.

00:08:40.179 --> 00:08:45.240
So what I decided to do was to
take my next six patients, all

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:48.350
with a serious illness,
and their families

00:08:48.350 --> 00:08:51.970
on their own personal
tour of our hospital.

00:08:51.970 --> 00:08:55.090
Some patients I brought to
our Intensive Care Unit.

00:08:55.090 --> 00:08:58.680
Other patients and families I
brought to our dialysis unit.

00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:00.970
And what every
person told me was

00:09:00.970 --> 00:09:04.880
that this was the most powerful
and empowering experience

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:06.320
that they had ever had.

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:08.030
That they couldn't
imagine making

00:09:08.030 --> 00:09:12.460
a decision about end-of-life
care without this tour.

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:14.500
Now, although the
nurses loved what

00:09:14.500 --> 00:09:18.070
I was doing-- they could see
the educational value in it--

00:09:18.070 --> 00:09:21.560
they quickly put an end
to my tour business.

00:09:21.560 --> 00:09:25.450
Because they knew I was breaking
patient confidentiality.

00:09:25.450 --> 00:09:28.580
So here's the conundrum
that I was left with.

00:09:28.580 --> 00:09:32.590
How could I recreate this
powerful and empowering

00:09:32.590 --> 00:09:36.140
experience for both
patients and families,

00:09:36.140 --> 00:09:39.860
and yet not break
patient confidentiality?

00:09:39.860 --> 00:09:41.960
And that's when I came
up with the idea--

00:09:41.960 --> 00:09:45.650
why not create short films
to help people better

00:09:45.650 --> 00:09:48.240
understand their options.

00:09:48.240 --> 00:09:49.830
So it's not just me.

00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:52.250
It's a group of
around 100 of us.

00:09:52.250 --> 00:09:57.400
We are 100 doctors,
nurses, patients, families,

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:01.190
and video artists from 10
academic medical centers

00:10:01.190 --> 00:10:03.150
who create these short videos.

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:05.490
But we don't just
create them, we actually

00:10:05.490 --> 00:10:09.450
study them in rigorous,
randomized control trials.

00:10:09.450 --> 00:10:11.800
And there's three
things that we find.

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:14.520
First, for patients who
have a serious illness

00:10:14.520 --> 00:10:17.940
and watch a video, they're more
informed about their options.

00:10:17.940 --> 00:10:21.090
They have much more knowledge
with which to understand

00:10:21.090 --> 00:10:22.830
their medical options.

00:10:22.830 --> 00:10:24.720
The second thing
is that for people

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:27.450
who have a serious illness
who have a conversation

00:10:27.450 --> 00:10:30.390
and use a video,
they actually tend

00:10:30.390 --> 00:10:33.160
to want more
comfort-oriented care.

00:10:33.160 --> 00:10:35.230
They make decisions
that lead them

00:10:35.230 --> 00:10:38.240
to end-of-life care
outside of the hospital,

00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:40.770
not tethered to
machines, and not

00:10:40.770 --> 00:10:43.280
in our Intensive Care Units.

00:10:43.280 --> 00:10:45.740
And the third thing is
when we asked people,

00:10:45.740 --> 00:10:48.550
are you comfortable watching
a video about goals of care

00:10:48.550 --> 00:10:52.720
at the end-of-life, people are
overwhelmingly comfortable.

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:55.830
We truly are a YouTube
generation where

00:10:55.830 --> 00:10:58.130
people expect these images.

00:10:58.130 --> 00:11:00.160
If a picture speaks
thousand words,

00:11:00.160 --> 00:11:03.880
videos speak hundreds
of thousands of words.

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:07.470
So what I thought I'd do is
show you one of our studies.

00:11:07.470 --> 00:11:10.020
And it was actually our
first study done right here

00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:12.800
at Massachusetts General
Hospital with patients

00:11:12.800 --> 00:11:15.250
who had advanced cancer.

00:11:15.250 --> 00:11:18.940
So what we did is we
took 50 patients, all

00:11:18.940 --> 00:11:22.640
with advanced cancer, and
we randomized the group

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:24.650
into two groups.

00:11:24.650 --> 00:11:27.880
The first group had
a verbal discussion

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:30.990
about what sort of medical
care they wanted now

00:11:30.990 --> 00:11:33.320
that they had advanced cancer.

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:35.950
We asked them, what
would you want now

00:11:35.950 --> 00:11:39.920
that you have advanced cancer,
and we gave them three options.

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:43.780
The other half of the group
had the same verbal discussion,

00:11:43.780 --> 00:11:47.650
but then they saw a short
video that actually showed them

00:11:47.650 --> 00:11:50.950
what each of their
goals of care entailed.

00:11:50.950 --> 00:11:53.840
Now, I know most of you
are not clinicians, but let

00:11:53.840 --> 00:11:57.310
me just give you the general
flavor of the goals of care.

00:11:57.310 --> 00:12:00.410
This is available
anywhere in America today.

00:12:00.410 --> 00:12:02.420
You generally have
three options.

00:12:02.420 --> 00:12:06.510
Life-prolonging care, limited
care, and comfort care.

00:12:06.510 --> 00:12:08.620
And I'll briefly
review each one.

00:12:08.620 --> 00:12:12.200
With life-prolonging care,
the goal is to prolong life.

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:15.720
It includes anything available
in a modern day hospital--

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:19.520
CPR, breathing machines,
the Intensive Care Unit.

00:12:19.520 --> 00:12:21.780
The middle category,
limited care,

00:12:21.780 --> 00:12:27.700
is essentially hospitalization
without the ICU, without CPR.

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:30.050
And the third
category, comfort care,

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:34.890
is essentially symptom relief,
really hospice level care.

00:12:34.890 --> 00:12:38.610
So those are the options
that all 50 patients had.

00:12:38.610 --> 00:12:41.850
But for the patients that
were randomized to the video,

00:12:41.850 --> 00:12:45.790
they got to see
visual images of each

00:12:45.790 --> 00:12:48.310
of those categories of care.

00:12:48.310 --> 00:12:52.100
Now, the particular video that
we created for these patients

00:12:52.100 --> 00:12:55.960
was a seven minute video, and
it was filmed and developed

00:12:55.960 --> 00:12:59.810
with an expert panel
of over 50 oncologists,

00:12:59.810 --> 00:13:03.210
intensivists, palliative
care doctors, nurses,

00:13:03.210 --> 00:13:07.710
social workers, chaplains,
patients with advanced cancer,

00:13:07.710 --> 00:13:11.000
and the families of patients
with advanced cancer.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.320
We wanted to make
sure that we offered

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:16.970
a fair and impartial
portrayal of what

00:13:16.970 --> 00:13:19.360
the options were for patients.

00:13:19.360 --> 00:13:22.720
Now, dealing with 50 people,
we bent over backwards

00:13:22.720 --> 00:13:26.110
to make sure that we
addressed everybody's concern.

00:13:26.110 --> 00:13:28.770
But you know the joke about
getting a bunch of oncologists

00:13:28.770 --> 00:13:32.110
together and asking them
an opinion on a patient,

00:13:32.110 --> 00:13:34.960
you'll get 50
different opinions.

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:37.110
This video took us
two years to make.

00:13:37.110 --> 00:13:41.370
Steven Spielberg makes probably
five films in two years.

00:13:41.370 --> 00:13:45.080
But we wanted to make sure that
patients and providers felt

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:49.430
that this was a fair
and impartial portrayal.

00:13:49.430 --> 00:13:55.200
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:57.640
-I'm Angelo Volandes, a
Physician at Harvard Medical

00:13:57.640 --> 00:13:58.490
School.

00:13:58.490 --> 00:14:01.370
Thank you for taking the time
to read "THE Conversation."

00:14:01.370 --> 00:14:03.710
It's been a privilege
caring for patients.

00:14:03.710 --> 00:14:07.110
Thank you for hearing their
stories and bearing witness.

00:14:07.110 --> 00:14:09.600
In this video I'll be
covering some of the topics

00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:11.490
that I touch on in
the book, so make

00:14:11.490 --> 00:14:14.840
sure to refer to the book for
more details and information.

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:17.080
Talking about medical
care at the end of life

00:14:17.080 --> 00:14:19.380
can sometimes be
difficult, but it doesn't

00:14:19.380 --> 00:14:21.470
have to be a sad conversation.

00:14:21.470 --> 00:14:24.640
There's a common three-step
approach to do it well.

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:27.620
The three steps are
start the process

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:29.740
and have the conversation.

00:14:29.740 --> 00:14:31.990
Talk to your loved
ones about your values

00:14:31.990 --> 00:14:33.720
and what's important to you.

00:14:33.720 --> 00:14:36.000
And then talk to
your health care team

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.270
about your medical choices.

00:14:38.270 --> 00:14:40.130
Let's review each
one of these steps

00:14:40.130 --> 00:14:43.490
so you can make sure you get
the right care at the right time

00:14:43.490 --> 00:14:44.960
and on your own terms.

00:14:51.570 --> 00:14:53.980
Don't wait for your doctor
to start the conversation.

00:14:53.980 --> 00:14:57.490
Start the discussion on your
own with family and friends.

00:14:57.490 --> 00:15:01.240
Here are four questions that
can help start the process.

00:15:01.240 --> 00:15:04.390
What kinds of things are
most important to you?

00:15:04.390 --> 00:15:07.080
What concerns do you have
about getting sick or needing

00:15:07.080 --> 00:15:09.250
medical care?

00:15:09.250 --> 00:15:12.850
If you were very sick, are there
any specific medical treatments

00:15:12.850 --> 00:15:15.350
that might be too much for you?

00:15:15.350 --> 00:15:18.120
And finally, what
are your spiritual,

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:21.180
philosophical, religious,
or cultural beliefs

00:15:21.180 --> 00:15:24.250
that would influence
your medical decisions?

00:15:24.250 --> 00:15:27.400
Considering these questions
is only the beginning.

00:15:27.400 --> 00:15:31.240
These reflections are not a
one-time event, but a process

00:15:31.240 --> 00:15:33.030
that you should
return to over time.

00:15:39.850 --> 00:15:42.180
After you've thought about
your values and wishes,

00:15:42.180 --> 00:15:44.513
it's important to share your
information with your loved

00:15:44.513 --> 00:15:45.110
ones.

00:15:45.110 --> 00:15:48.130
Holidays are a good time to
start having these discussions

00:15:48.130 --> 00:15:50.570
with the people you
would want to be around

00:15:50.570 --> 00:15:52.700
if you became very sick.

00:15:52.700 --> 00:15:54.947
Pick a calm and
quiet place to talk.

00:15:54.947 --> 00:15:57.030
The talk doesn't have to
have a certain structure,

00:15:57.030 --> 00:15:58.900
let it just happen.

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:00.650
And you don't need to
establish everything

00:16:00.650 --> 00:16:02.750
with one conversation.

00:16:02.750 --> 00:16:05.330
After the conversation
I often tell my patients

00:16:05.330 --> 00:16:08.400
to use their cell phone or
tablet to film themselves

00:16:08.400 --> 00:16:11.920
telling their loved ones what
is most important in their lives

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:13.670
regarding medical care.

00:16:13.670 --> 00:16:16.380
They can then send
the video to them.

00:16:16.380 --> 00:16:19.130
And if you are ready,
complete the appropriate legal

00:16:19.130 --> 00:16:20.520
paperwork.

00:16:20.520 --> 00:16:23.370
Now you're ready to complete
the last step, talking

00:16:23.370 --> 00:16:24.495
with your health care team.

00:16:30.940 --> 00:16:33.130
Talking with your
doctor is vital,

00:16:33.130 --> 00:16:35.970
since he or she will know
your medical condition best

00:16:35.970 --> 00:16:37.440
and will be able
to help translate

00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:41.134
your preferences into an
actionable medical plan.

00:16:41.134 --> 00:16:42.550
There are three
general approaches

00:16:42.550 --> 00:16:45.590
to medical care for
people who are very sick.

00:16:45.590 --> 00:16:50.710
They are life-prolonging
care, limited medical care

00:16:50.710 --> 00:16:52.850
and comfort care.

00:16:52.850 --> 00:16:55.850
The first approach is
life-prolonging care.

00:16:55.850 --> 00:16:58.880
With this option the
focus is to lengthen life.

00:16:58.880 --> 00:17:01.280
This includes all medical
care that is available

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:05.470
in the hospital like
CPR, breathing machines,

00:17:05.470 --> 00:17:07.750
and treatments in the ICU.

00:17:07.750 --> 00:17:11.609
For healthy people, CPR has
a good chance of success

00:17:11.609 --> 00:17:14.290
and has improved over time.

00:17:14.290 --> 00:17:17.260
However, for people with
an advanced illness,

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:21.069
CPR's overall
effectiveness is not high.

00:17:21.069 --> 00:17:23.480
It's important to
ask your doctor

00:17:23.480 --> 00:17:27.760
what the chances are that CPR
will work in someone like you.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:31.420
Sometimes people decide to try
life-prolonging interventions

00:17:31.420 --> 00:17:33.320
for a short period of time.

00:17:33.320 --> 00:17:35.680
And if the interventions
are not successful

00:17:35.680 --> 00:17:40.910
they move to the next
option, limited medical care.

00:17:40.910 --> 00:17:43.110
With limited medical
care, the focus

00:17:43.110 --> 00:17:45.860
is to take care of
treatable problems.

00:17:45.860 --> 00:17:48.890
People who choose this
approach want medical care that

00:17:48.890 --> 00:17:51.560
will help restore their health.

00:17:51.560 --> 00:17:54.990
My father received
limited medical care.

00:17:54.990 --> 00:17:58.710
He had IV medications
with careful monitoring.

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:02.430
But he did not want any
life-prolonging interventions

00:18:02.430 --> 00:18:05.200
like CPR and breathing machines.

00:18:05.200 --> 00:18:07.380
He chose to avoid
these procedures,

00:18:07.380 --> 00:18:10.770
even though he might
have died without them.

00:18:10.770 --> 00:18:13.380
The third approach
is comfort care.

00:18:13.380 --> 00:18:16.860
With comfort care, the main
goal is to be comfortable.

00:18:16.860 --> 00:18:20.090
Treatments are only used if they
help make people feel better

00:18:20.090 --> 00:18:22.649
and improve their
quality of life.

00:18:22.649 --> 00:18:24.440
People who choose this
approach are usually

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:30.160
treated at home, in hospice,
or sometimes in a nursing home.

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:32.590
Talk to your doctor
and your loved ones.

00:18:32.590 --> 00:18:34.290
If you let them
know your choices,

00:18:34.290 --> 00:18:35.960
they can help make
sure that you are

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:39.950
at the center of and in
control of your care.

00:18:39.950 --> 00:18:41.830
Thank you for taking
this journey with me

00:18:41.830 --> 00:18:44.650
and hearing the lives of
some extraordinary people.

00:18:44.650 --> 00:18:47.440
Their stories are our stories.

00:18:47.440 --> 00:18:47.990
Take care.

